export const batch125 = {
  'decoded.json': {
    base: { id: 'decoded', title: 'Decoded', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781657487215 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A hidden guide inside us points to our favorite brands',
        text: 'Most ads fade fast, yet a few stay with people for years. The Cadbury chocolate campaign earned many creative awards. In the spot, a gorilla listens to music, then drums the beat. The candy bar appears only at the end. By spotlighting one brand, Cadbury turned into a marketing success. The reason some campaigns win is not easy to explain. Neuroeconomist Peter Kenning ran a study showing that people often buy on gut feel. They will reach for a familiar option, even when many choices are on the shelf. The brain leans on what feels known. Psychologist Daniel Kahneman, a founder of behavioral economics and a Nobel winner, says two systems drive our choices. One system handles perception and gut reactions, sorting input by feel. The other handles careful thought. Strong brands are read by the first system. Smart marketers learn to switch on that system for buyers. The second system burns energy, so people default to the first. Think of the gut system as the autopilot and the thinking system as the pilot. Marketer Phil Barden spent 25 years studying how shoppers pick one brand over another. Knowing the buyer and shaping a product to fit their needs sits at the heart of good marketing. Barden went on to build fresh methods for brand positioning and ad design. Brand mentions and ad views climbed. His growing interest in buyer psychology led him to join Decode, a research firm founded by a scientist of decision-making. Barden chose to share what he learned about the link between choice and marketing, and to map the real forces behind a purchase. Every product carries a soft value, what experts call brand equity. People pay a lot for coffee at Starbucks, then return again and again. Coffee is part of it, but something else is too. Once we look at shopping through the lens of neuroscience and cognitive psychology, the hidden reasons for buying start to show. Decoded lays out the science of why we buy. You will see why love of a brand can beat product quality, which visual cues grab the eye, and how framing shifts what we notice.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The mood a brand builds can matter more than the offer',
        text: 'The autopilot system takes in the world through the senses. A new skill needs focus at first, then becomes automatic over time. The autopilot handles a heavy load of input. When you land on a website, your brain scans color, layout, and feel in a flash. The marketing message has to land fast. It must stick, draw you in, and stay short. Your first impression of a brand forms in about one second. The autopilot learns from every signal that comes in. A child hears the word no in a sharp tone and files that sound away. When a pattern repeats, the brain marks it as a likely signal of what comes next. Specific images, words, or sounds in ads build links in the mind. Shoppers spend long stretches in stores and pick what feels right to them. The setting around a choice also shapes it. In one test, people helped each other more often in stores that smelled of fresh bread or coffee. The framing effect is real. Back to Starbucks, why do people pay more for the same drink. The mood of warmth, the music, the room itself, all of it adds up. The framing a brand lays down can pull people back again and again. Marketing and sales teams argue about whether to chase ad quality or brand image. The truth is these need to work together. The brand quietly sets a stage that shapes how the buyer sees value. Most buyers never spot the framing effect at work. The autopilot runs across many brain regions, hidden from thought. The autopilot takes in the world through the five senses, so marketing tactics aim at those senses.'
      },
      {
        title: 'We pay up with a grin when a purchase feels worth it',
        text: 'The framing of a brand sets an expectation in the mind of the buyer. If the buyer views the brand in a warm light, the product will carry that glow. Our view, and so the experience of the product, comes mostly from hidden autopilot work, as Phil Barden has written. When we see a product we want, parts of the brain tied to wanting light up. Add a price, and the lobe tied to pain also switches on. The brain pairs the cost with a small sting. If the pleasure outweighs the pain, we tend to buy. The gap is called net value. Smart brands work to lift the pleasure side so the price feels fair to the buyer. The pleasure from buying should top the sting of spending. The next move is to load the product with extra value. Take the Norwegian water brand Voss, which gets part of its pull from bottle design. People see the water as special because it shows up in high end places. Price shapes the view of value too. Buyers feel the water must be great, because it costs a lot. In one test, people tasted two wines and rated the costlier one higher, but the bottles were the same. Words can lift a product too. The headline, the ad copy, and the label all push us toward a buy. For example, a restaurant dish with a vivid name can make you crave it more. If you want an ad to focus on the gain, try words like discover, get, more, or help. If you want to stop a buyer from losing out, try words like no risk, avoid, without, or free. You can also reshape the price itself by making it feel like a win. Language that points to value can change the real feel. For example, instead of 25 percent fat, say 75 percent meat without fat. Promotional cues, like red numbers or a price tag with a sparkle, push the buyer to think discount. Comparing a product to others that cost more, or putting up sale signs, are two more ways to draw buyers in.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The buyer senses more than meets the eye',
        text: 'Time is another resource buyers care about. Phil Barden shares ways to make waits feel shorter. First, walk the customer to the place where the problem gets explained, and they will sit tight for the fix. Second, stock the waiting area with a TV or books so the time passes. Try to remove the feeling of doubt, and the wait should always pay off. Value also turns on the effort it takes to buy. Smooth paths help a lot. For example, instead of forcing people to sign up on a site before they can buy, let them create an account after, and frame it as a way to speed up future buys. Choice drives demand. You can buy warm water on a hot day, but a cold drink wins every time. We are ready to pay more when we lack a direct sample to compare against. Our sense of value rests on comparing one option to another. Context shapes the value of a product in a strong way. A situation can trigger a memory and pull us toward a specific item. For example, the phrase ice cream brand as a dessert for Christmas narrows the field more than just ice cream brand does. Aim to be number one for a specific situation. Hunt for spots other brands have not claimed. Picture the situations you want tied to your brand, and the sales may grow. Sight plays a big role in choice. We need to see what we plan to buy. Visual focus lands on a small area while the rest fades. Marketers tap into side vision to boost the effect. Walking through a store, you spot the shape and color of a familiar washing powder box from the corner of your eye. You do not need to stop and stare to find it. The product should still look good when blurred. Build a brand that the eye can spot fast.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Your brand does not live outside its setting',
        text: 'The brain does not take in the whole image, but it can spot many objects and pull them into a clear scene. We can pick out the make of a car even when we have never seen that model before. The same skill applies to brands and products. Whatever words you write in the style of the Coca-Cola logo, your mind still hears a Coke drink. When you launch a new product or change a brand look, think about what holds the recognition together. Visual cues like shape, color, and font build the picture. Round logos, for example, often feel more friendly. The brain reads the object and what it means in a flash. Brand cues should match the hopes and goals of the buyer. Brand cues should send clear and warm messages to customers. Barden points to a juice package that had a picture of an orange. After a refresh, the pack showed a glass of juice, meant to signal high status. Sales fell, because that kind of glass shows up in hotels, not in daily home life. The setting of the ad matters too. Take the diamond image, for example. In ads for building materials, a diamond stands for hardness. In ads for hair dye, it stands for shine. The autopilot likes simple input that takes little work to process. Spelling a name in capital letters slows the reader down. The wider the gap between the real price and the marked down price on a tag, the bigger the deal seems. A face is a key tool in marketing too. The pleasure center of the brain lights up at the sight of an attractive face. It does not have to be a person. Animal faces and emojis can pull the same kind of look. We look at faces without thinking. We also tend to look where the person in the ad is looking. When the model looks at the product instead of at us, we tend to grow curious about the product, even if we do not notice it. An umbrella brand is a way to sell several product lines under one name. Big umbrella brands include Apple, Nestle, and P and G.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Change the plan, not the customer',
        text: 'How a product is shown shapes how it is seen. Tweaks in the shopping flow can change choices without changing beliefs. For example, Google revamped its office canteens to nudge staff toward healthy food. The line now starts with salads, and rich desserts are placed in dull containers instead of clear ones. The choices shifted, but the beliefs did not. A behavior shift can spark a self image loop, where past actions shape what we do next. Your view of a healthy salad can change after you pick it for a few days in a row. Here is another example, a man bought flowers for his mother in law after his team won, simply because he was in a good mood. Next time he will buy a bouquet again, since showing up empty handed would feel rude. The buy becomes a habit, mood aside. Most buys happen without a plan. Even when a shopper knows what they want, the layout of the store can change their mind. Three rules guide most shopping trips. First, tangibility. The cues we get should be clear. Paying a monthly gym fee, for example, can push a person to show up more often. Second, speed. The autopilot wants needs met fast. We settle for a small reward today over a bigger one a year from now. Make sure your buyers can taste the result as soon as possible. Third, confidence. We lean toward safe and steady options, and we tend to pick what others seem to pick. The brain runs wanting and liking on different circuits. You can like a cozy bookshop and still order a book from a website. Buyers act on wanting and the hope of a reward, not just on a warm feeling. The more a service matters, the more we will pay. Name the problems your product solves and show clear answers. The value of a product is not how pretty it looks, but how well it meets the buyer goal.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The buyer motive should always point to the goal',
        text: 'Whenever someone mentions a product or service, your brand should be the first that comes to mind. That reach is a key sign of brand health. Goals steer positioning and strategy, so you need to pin down what your product should fulfill. Goals shape what we pay attention to. Goals form and run below the level of thought. We make hundreds of small choices a day. The stronger the link between a brand and a goal, the more likely we are to think of that brand in a given moment. The hope of a reward makes a buy feel rich. In the Bounty ad, a girl tastes a chocolate bar and flowers bloom around her. Buyers know this is a fantasy. Still, they get a real sense of the joy the product can bring. The expectation effect is a strong force. The two main drivers are promotion and prevention. A drill, for example, serves the clear goal of making holes. It also hides a deeper goal, saving effort and lifting output. That second layer hits the need for promotion. Brain science has mapped other universal drives in people, including safety, pleasure, adventure, autonomy, and excitement. Brand promotion should start with clear goals. For example, the top deodorant is the one that best blocks sweat and smell. After that base, brands can reach for hidden goals. In the juice rebranding case, the firm lost a lot of money with the wrong move. The old ad hinted at taking care of the family with fresh juice. The new look missed that promise, and a fancy glass did not carry the warm meaning. Feelings can get in the way of good marketing. We feel strong emotions when we reach a goal. The goals are sharp, but the feelings are wide. Barden suggests positioning brands by goals, not by feelings. We can be creative in how we express the brand, as long as we keep the link between cues and goals strong, as Phil Barden has put it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Reaching the hidden layer of decision-making is a way to give your brand fresh meaning. The skill to read the real goals of buyers and send the right cues helps you understand shoppers. Studying the link between clear and hidden needs sharpens your strategy. When you buy washing powder, you look for clean clothes, but also for a way to care for yourself and your family. Ads should send a cue of protection. Goals give you a sharper way to plan. The skill to read images and patterns in the world on a gut level is the root of human awareness. People from the same culture tend to read cues, ideas, and goals in similar ways. Those links sit below thought. So companies that sell across borders should mind the differences in mindset. When a brand links to many goals, the value of each one fades. Aim at one goal and show that your brand leads the field. Do not lean on emotion alone. A pitch that is only facts or only feelings will miss how the brand can meet a buyer goal. Send clear cues that show the product meets the buyer need. Think like a customer. What do they want when they reach for the kind of product you sell. Hunt for clear and deep motives, and you can build a pitch that truly lands. Try this. Think of the main goal tied to your brand. What hidden need of the buyer should it serve. The choice could be safety, which means caring for the family, or pleasure, which means rest, or excitement, which means fun and curiosity, or adventure, which means freedom and courage, or autonomy, which means success and power, or discipline, which means order and precision. Once you set the goal, strategy and ad cues get easier to pick. If you have read to the end, well done.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'descartes-error.json': {
    base: { id: 'descartes-error', title: "Descartes' Error", author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781615203873 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'The mind and body are not two separate things',
        text: 'French thinker René Descartes argued that the mind stood apart from the body, working without any physical pull. People accepted this view for years and called it Cartesian Dualism. They labeled the mind as immaterial and the body as material. The body is not whole without the mind, and the mind is not whole without the body. Research by Antonio Damasio has shown the opposite. The mind is in fact shaped by the body. When people suffer heavy damage to their frontal lobes, their outward behavior often shifts in striking ways. Damage to the frontal lobe of the brain has been linked to a number of odd shifts in behavior. People who were once cool and steady can swing to extremes. Doctors call this the Gage syndrome, named for the famous railroad foreman Phineas Gage. He survived a brutal accident in which an iron rod shot through his left eye and out the base of his skull, tearing through much of his frontal lobe. The brain is the home of the mind, and it must be shielded from harm or both mind and body will pay. Before the accident, Phineas Gage was warm, social, and quick witted. He did not lose his motor skills, but he became a different man. Mood swings and bursts of anger made it hard to hold a job, and a man who had lived in comfort found himself in poverty by age 25. The self is a state the body keeps rebuilding, as Antonio Damasio has written.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The brain runs a set of networks that support its work',
        text: 'Much of what we know about the brain comes from neuroanatomy, the study of the structure and layout of the nervous system. We now know that the brain has separate, segregated, and defined systems. That means we can read a person behavior by studying their brain activity. We know only a little of how the brain works, but that little can guide us in reading the body. With Gage syndrome, there is no quick way to tie a specific behavior to a clear part of the brain. There is no big shift on the outside, so you have to watch the new traits show up in daily life before you can be sure a change has happened. Physical changes from frontal lobe damage are often missed because they are subtle. The brain is a system of smaller systems, and each one can be used to track a change in a person. The Gage case happened at a time when deep brain study was hard, so it was set aside. Modern tools in neuroanatomy have made it possible to spot and treat many brain conditions. His case became a reference point for studies to this day and a spark for the work of Damasio, who set out to challenge the Descartes view. He wanted to trace a physical change, such as an injury, to a clear shift in mood or behavior.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Emotions are not the enemy of reason but shape our choices',
        text: 'Neuroanatomy also teaches us about emotion and reason, two forces that often pull against each other and shape how we decide. We tend to think emotions cloud our judgment, but in fact they help us choose well. How we act is shaped by how we think, a theme that runs through both philosophy and science. Descartes is known for the line I think, therefore I am, which also frames the person as driven by the mind. It is striking that Descartes himself saw the mind as a thing apart from the body. Most of what we do, on purpose or not, is shaped by emotion. We should also admit that much of what we do comes from either emotion or reason. But are they truly separate. They are not. The set of brain systems that handle clear thought also handle feeling. The brain does not split emotion and reason into separate parts, both rise from the same networks. Plenty of emotion can muddy reason and cloud our view. That is the case when it runs hot, or so we thought. It turns out that too little emotion can also throw reason off. In cases of frontal lobe damage, a person loses most of their empathy, which often leads to poor choices.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Reason and feeling meet to give us a clearer view',
        text: 'Damasio put forward a theory to explain the science of rationality. He points to four factors that shape how we handle the issue. First, choices in complex settings call for clear reasoning strategies. Second, feelings play a key role in the body biological regulation. Third, the brain builds and rebuilds many images. Fourth, the brain can hold those images through a large store of memory. These factors come together to shape how we read the world. How we do that rests on the link between reason and choice, and on the link between feelings and emotions. It is the meeting of feeling and reason that gives us sound and clear headed choices. The two are often used as if they were the same, but they are not. Feelings are a complex process, trickier to pull apart. Feelings are the body side of a conscious process, a way the body reacts. Emotions, on the other hand, are the lived experience of those body reactions. Feelings are full, complex states, while emotions are how those states show up in us. In other words, feelings give shape to emotion, and without feelings we would not grasp our own emotions. There are two kinds of emotion, primary and secondary. Primary emotions are the primal ones, like fear and worry, that rise from the amygdala. Primary emotions are the base reactions we evolved to face daily life. Secondary emotions rise from a more measured process. Instead of a quick flash, they come from the link between close observation and the first primary emotion. The human mind can feel two clashing emotions at the same time and can sense many physical feelings too, and the brain can read them all with surprising skill.'
      },
      {
        title: 'We can map our reactions through somatic markers',
        text: 'The secondary emotional process matters a lot when it comes to avoiding rash choices that would happen without it. Secondary emotional pathways are those where feeling and reason both shape the final call. If we lean only on primary emotions, we tend to make worse choices most of the time. The role of feeling in choice is often missed because many think feelings get in the way of clear thinking. But without feelings, there is no real reasoning in our choices. So the partnership has to work if we want clear and steady ways to express what we feel. Reason feels hollow if it is not backed by a clear expression of feeling. The key to this union is the somatic marker. Somatic markers are feelings tied to emotions directly, often paired with body signs like a racing heart or sweat. Think of them as the cues that tell you when a strong primary emotion is running hot, or not. The body side of emotion helps shape choices that can be quick or slow. Somatic markers do more than steer choices. They also act as a kind of signal for reward and pleasure. Patients with frontal lobe damage or other brain injury pay less attention to reward and satisfaction when they do a task. People with heavy frontal lobe damage show little activity in the reward center. They carry out tasks as part of a routine without any real pleasure. The same pattern shows up in some people with psychopathy, where the cause may be unusual growth in that brain region during fetal life. It is more proof that the mind shapes the body and the body shapes the mind.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The Descartes error showed us the link between mind and body',
        text: 'So what was the Descartes error, and how does Damasio try to fix it. In short, René Descartes was sure that human beings exist as a working pair. He called it a metaphysical pair, meaning the mind and body, feeling and reason, are together and yet apart. The pair of mind and body is one that both sets them apart and ties them together. We have learned that this is hardly true. Much of what the body does, on purpose or not, is steered by emotion. Social shifts in people can be traced to a brain change caused by injury or by what did or did not happen in the brain during fetal growth. The mind plays a key role in how the body works, and any flaw in one shows up in the other. Think of the mind as the software that runs on the hardware, which is the body. Without the body, the mind is a floating thing with no anchor. Without the mind, the body is a lifeless shell. The mind and body are a true pair, but unlike the Descartes view, they are linked and always shaping each other, with neither in charge. The mind is the driver and the body is the vehicle, and both need each other to work well. In metaphysics, you can in theory pull the mind away from the body. That may have fed the metaphysical pair idea, since people once thought of humans as a sum of two parts. Metaphysics does not fully grasp the mind body pair, because it sets aside their dependence. The error was to treat body and mind as separate. Damasio set out to argue that the mind is embodied, meaning it has full form inside and with the body. Although Damasio meant to correct the error, he ended up linking his view to the one he was correcting.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'The place of neuroanatomy in modern life is hard to overstate, since it gives us a window into how the brain works with the body. The old view was that the brain and mind stood apart from the body, but that does not hold up. It would mean the mind could walk off and come back when it felt like it. That might pass in metaphysics, but not in real life, since there is no scientific proof and since Damasio has done so much research in neuroanatomy and neurology. He argues that mind and body work in a smooth unity, not apart. The body acts and works in direct response to the mind, and the body balance called homeostasis leans on the mind neural network. The mind is just a soft entity that comes to life through the physical web of nerves, muscles, and neurons in the brain. With that in mind, neither can work without the other, and the behavior of one always shows up in the other. The Descartes error was to see either as a stand alone thing, and Damasio fixed that by showing they depend on each other. Try this. The mind and body are basically one, so it pays to take care of both. You can try meditation and physical exercise to bring them into better tune. If you read to the end, well done.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'design-for-the-real-world.json': {
    base: { id: 'design-for-the-real-world', title: 'Design for the Real World', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781615280940 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Useful design is a pillar of modern life and deserves care',
        text: 'Design is a key part of daily life, since almost everything around us is shaped by it. It shows up in many fields, from writing a poem to raising a building, painting a mural, baking a cake, or writing a concerto. We often miss how much design shapes our lives, yet it is woven into every part of them. Without careful and thoughtful design, we would lose many of the things we count on each day. Design is the conscious and intuitive effort to bring meaningful order. It follows that design has to be meaningful, but no one has set a fixed rule for what it must look like. The only test that really matters is whether it works. If an item does not work, it holds no real meaning. Six parts decide if a design is good or not. First, method, the smooth blend and best use of tools, materials, and process. Second, use, does it work and is it easy to handle. Third, need, it must meet the needs of the target audience. Fourth, telesis, it should fit the times and the conditions. Fifth, association, people should be able to relate to the design and want it. Sixth, aesthetics, it should appeal to the target audience and ideally to a wider circle as well. If you want to see how design works in the real world, you have come to the right summary. Read on to pick up some useful facts.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Simple choices can bring new problems, so look past short term wins',
        text: 'Society moves at a fast clip, which makes design more layered and harder to predict. Design is core to the human story, and it now goes beyond the designer intent and the buyer need. Every effort has a wide reach that shapes a big part of human life. There have been many cases in which smartphones overheat and burst. The designer set out to give buyers a quality handheld device with sharp speed and a crisp display. The design hits its mark as a tool that delivers quality and speed, but it also harms the world, since heavy use can cause overheating. Unlike in past years, designers now face a number of tough calls in planning, creating, and shipping a product. Simple designs, like a can of food, bring ease but can also cause harm through the preservatives in the food. Design has to look past human need and keep safety in view. Because of these stakes, designers are now expected to play more than one role. They are asked to act as therapist, doctor, lawyer, and layperson all at once. Their work is no longer just about a happy buyer. It has become a tool that can make life or break it. The market is also crowded, so designers have to stay sharp to keep up. Instead of designing what society needs, many designers chase a small group of buyers who bring in big returns. In the early 1990s, design was mostly about style. Take furniture, for example. Even when it cost a lot and was not comfortable, people wanted it because it fit the look they wanted for their social standing. Much of the clothing from the 1990s was not comfortable, but people wore it with pride because of the elegance tied to the look. The first iPhone came out in 2007, and it has since sold more than 700 million units, making it one of the best designs of our time.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Designers should aim for meaning over sheer output',
        text: 'The flood of empty and useless design has taken over the work of many designers. Rather than build things that are truly useful, they now make products that are easy to toss. These items are for short term fun, and they have little real use. The time spent on these throwaway pieces could have gone into work that has real value for society. It is easy to buy into a fad, but these items rarely hold any value. They might be hot for a few months, then end up in the bin. A good example is the fidget spinner, sold as a tool to help focus and lower stress. How many do you see now. Not many. The fidget spinner is a perfect case of pointless design and wasted time. You have to pick between making sense and making money if you want to be a designer, as R. Buckminster Fuller once said. Before the days of tight budgets, people changed cars every three years because they were told a car that old was out of date. Because of that, car makers began to build low quality cars that barely lasted three years. In 1977, the American car industry recalled about 10.4 million vehicles even though it had sold only 9.3 million new cars that year. These makers are not pushed to build the best product for the long haul. The short term win of cheap output blinds them. Too many designers crank out new products to make money. Real designers focus on human need and long term use.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Design mistakes can hurt people and the wider world',
        text: 'Every action has a result, and in many cases the result is a negative one. We should also note that being a designer is not easy. Like a surgeon, a designer has no room for error. With heavy duties on their shoulders, designers sometimes fail, and the fallout can be huge. For example, disposable plastic and polyethylene are very useful. They make shopping and carrying goods easy, and they are simple to consume. The intent behind disposables is good, but the harms far outweigh the help. These disposables are usually thrown out in the wrong way, leading to pollution of air, land, and water. There are billions of plastic pieces in the sea, floating and clogging the water. This may be one of the biggest design mistakes in the world. The most important things a designer can do are to spot, isolate, define, and solve problems. Problems come up every day, which is why more designers are needed around the world. Creative thinking means a designer has to be bold enough to step past old limits. In stepping past these limits, designers run into blocks that can hold back their work. These blocks show up as perception blocks, emotional blocks, association blocks, cultural blocks, professional blocks, intellectual blocks, and environmental blocks. To get past these blocks, designers have to pay close attention. They can do this through brainstorming and through fresh, new ways of thinking, using proven tools to ship a top quality design. Some design errors come from powerful myths built on shaky facts. Five myths shape the thinking of many industrial designers today. They are the myth of mass production, the myth of obsolescence, the myth of what people want, the myth of the designer lack of control, and the myth that quality no longer matters. They are myths for a reason, since they are not true. The key thing to remember in this whole talk is that designing products and services for what people need is more important than creating what they want. When you design, make sure it is something that lifts the quality of life. Usefulness and long life are the goal.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Pollution from bad design puts the planet at risk',
        text: 'Pollution cannot be brushed aside when we aim for a healthy world. Across the globe, huge numbers of people have been hurt or disabled by toxic waste. The defoliant Agent Orange scarred the genes of people in Vietnam. Bomb test zones in Nevada and Utah have triggered bone cancer and blood cancer in nearby populations. Every region on earth carries some form of contamination, and with each new wave of growth, the danger grows. Many industrial products are poorly conceived because the makers chase earnings over craft. Pollution cuts deeper than throwaway cups or oily rivers. If we let our guard down, it can threaten the survival of our species. People have cut deep into forests and scraped across deserts. Tree clearing runs far ahead of tree planting, and the public tunes out the environmental warnings issued each year. The result could reshape daily life within a generation, possibly putting human survival itself on the line. To put it plainly, every human pursuit is built on design, because shaping any action toward a chosen outcome is a design exercise, in the words of Victor Papanek. Close to one percent of the remaining tropical canopy disappears every year. Wildlife teeters on the edge of vanishing, while crops struggle because the soil has been saturated with synthetic chemicals. All of this can be dialed back when design is done with care. Designers can play a real role in curbing the damage and stopping new harm. For example, two well known designers named John Maurice and James Aronson built a program that ships young trees abroad for replanting. Through their design, they drove a meaningful boost in forest restoration.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Integrated designers can change the world when profit is not the only goal',
        text: 'Learning should be an experience that brings a sense of joy, according to journalist George B. Leonard. Education for designers is based on learning many things and unlearning others. They should tap into the wisdom that nature shows, instead of following the old teaching methods. Thinking outside the box is key in many situations. When it comes to design, fresh and creative thinking wins over following the same old routines. Bringing together many factors to reach a complete design is key. This process is called integrated design. With integrated design, designers come to see how important it is to bring different parts of life into their choices. Those choices go a long way in shaping the world now and later on. For integrated design to work, designers have to learn several schools of thought. They must know why they should design, when, and what it means for society as a whole. Integrated design takes a full circle view. Designers must understand how a product or service will affect everything and everyone around it. Integrated design calls for a team of strong minds across many fields. The team main focus cannot be profit making. It has to be the order and safety of people and society. Their job is to find problems, isolate them, and then fix them. An integrated design team can be behind a massive change in how we survive. With a growing population and new tools, the world now leans on design to survive more than ever. Car companies are focusing more on reliability and long life, not just looks. The big shift in design ideas is driven by professionals from many fields coming together. Designers should study the impact of design on religion, culture, tradition, and the economy. These studies prepare them to make the right calls on strategy. It is also important to stop making products just to make a profit. The current and next generation of young and hopeful designers is a real source of hope for design. They have seen the impact of design on society, and many want to use their craft to change the world. Design is more than beauty and grace. It is a way of life that deserves careful study.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Design is an art, a steady way to create beauty and to protect life. Its true heart is in the planning and the making, and that is why it deserves the closest study. As a designer, you should never lose sight of putting the needs of people first. Victor Papanek was always ahead of his time. He was the first designer to focus on sustainability and on the impact of design on the world. It is easy to crank out products that people think they want, but these often end up in the trash soon after. Wants change all the time, like the wind, but needs tend to stick around for much longer. As a steady and successful designer, it is key to serve the needs of people before you even think about wants. Yes, you can weave in small details to please the wish list, but the focus should be on needs. Doing that is the ethical path, and it also means the item you make will last a long time. The slow and steady path is always better than a huge hit that ends in a steep crash. Too many designers chase the fast buck without thinking about whether what they are making will still be needed a few years, or even a few months, from now. It is also key to think about the impact on the world, since much of the harm that has been done is hard to undo. Try this. Avoid making designs for the sole aim of profit. Make designs because you want to lift the lives of people and improve the world. Work out how to focus on what people need while adding small touches of what they may want. That way you cover all sides. Put together a team of seasoned people who will stand by you through the design process. A few strong minds help you make designs that last. If you have read to the end, well done.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'designing-the-mind-the-principles-of-psychitecture.json': {
    base: { id: 'designing-the-mind-the-principles-of-psychitecture', title: 'Designing the Mind', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781657592570 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Taking charge of how we think',
        text: 'When someone insults us, the deeper mind pushes us to make them regret the words. Our self worth drops as we chew on the slight for days or weeks, replaying what we should have said for hours. Sick of the endless stream of dark thoughts, we often wish we could turn off our brains so we would not feel sorrow, regret, or misery. It may look impossible, but we are not as stuck as we think. With the right tools, any of us can rewrite the mental software we run. The first step is to see that our less helpful patterns can act like code, much like software. In this frame, the insult is the input that kicks off a program, and the broken loop drives us to question our worth. As a result, we feel small and act without thinking. So what can we do to change this. Enter Psychitecture, a self growth method that helps us build our abilities. Drawing on the breakthroughs of cognitive therapy and humanistic psychology, it offers a fresh, modern way to upgrade the mind. With its ideas and tools, we can become the makers of our skills, habits, and futures. Picture your goals each day to sharpen focus and drive. If the idea of sharpening your thinking excites you, you have chosen the right summary. Dive into the hidden layers of the mind to unlock your full potential and become a true master of self control. Ready for an exciting trip of self discovery. Let us begin.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Upgrading the hardware and the software',
        text: 'Across history, the leading tech of each era has shaped how we think about the mind. In Ancient Greece, philosophers tied the psyche to a chariot. During the Enlightenment, they used the metaphor of a clock. Today, we compare the brain to a computer, our most advanced machine. The hardware runs on neurons, neurotransmitters, and nerve signals. The software is the psyche. Together, they make the brain the most complex system ever built. Now for some practical steps. How can you boost the hardware. Start by tracking your sleep, diet, and activity. Plenty of tools can help you keep an eye on them. If you spot a gap, it may be time to see a health expert. By tuning these core habits, you will soon see real gains in mental clarity and performance. Your mind will get sharper, more focused, and ready to take on any challenge with ease. Another example is medicine. Drugs and surgery are already helping with brain disorders, lifting brain function and healing. Transhumanism, the view that we should use science and tech to boost our bodies and minds, pushes us to aim higher. It wants to take human nature to a new level by changing our bodies and minds. Under this view, future drugs and tiny brain implants may fix, regrow, and refresh damaged cells. Genetic engineering may lift our IQ, our creativity, and even our looks. Still, most of these new tools are in early stages. So a more direct and reliable way to boost our thinking is software transhumanism. This method helps us reach our potential without leaning on advanced tech. Matching beliefs and actions with goals is the key to feeding the mind. Another way to rewire the mind is to learn new things and build fresh neural paths. The trick is to grow links in the brain that match our goals and hopes.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Self awareness and steady effort are our superpowers',
        text: 'First and foremost, we should believe in our ability to reach good results. We need to set aside the idea that some people are born to win while others are stuck. Innate ability matters, but it is not the only force that shapes our fate, and the 10,000 hour rule from Canadian writer Malcolm Gladwell shows why. Under this rule, the special talents of people like Nikola Tesla, Elon Musk, and Ludwig van Beethoven come from years of deep practice. It is not a perfect formula for picking the next Grammy winner, but it shows the power of training. Studies also confirm that the simple belief in our capacity to grow opens the path to success. It is not self talk. It is a program that taps into the power of neuroplasticity, the brain ability to form and reshape synaptic links. It lets us slowly get better at avoiding mistakes and breaking bad habits through steady and long effort. So how do we tap into this brain power. The most promising tool is self awareness. Let us be honest. Every mind is its own universe. Even scientists do not fully know what our inner worlds share and where they differ. It leads to a clear point. No one can read how we see life better than we can. Some call it mindfulness, others call it metacognition, but the heart is the same. We should rise above our actions, thoughts, and feelings and watch them. These three pieces form the pillars of the psyche, and if we really want to rewire the software, we need to see how they work. Bush argues that they work like if then rules. For example, if we have a certain thought, we feel a certain feeling. By changing our beliefs, we can change how we feel. Chasing goals, not just hitting them, is where the deepest joy lives. By digging into the triggers that shape our thoughts, feelings, and actions, we can know ourselves better and use that knowledge to reach our goals. It is not an easy path, and there is no single answer to all our issues. Still, the real value of self growth is the path, not the final stop.'
      },
      {
        title: 'How to break past our biases',
        text: 'Managing the mind leans heavily on the thinking side. If left unchecked, false ideas create a gap between our views and reality, locking us inside self made limits. For example, the consistency bias makes us stick to our habits and beliefs to look logical. Yet that path can also hold us back. Why does this matter. Our beliefs shape most software functions, like our choices and feelings. So biases in thought will spread to other areas, slowing all our efforts. That is why building clear and fair reasoning is a proven way to redesign the mind. Biases come from the human habit of simplifying complex thoughts and processes. For example, people widely accept that memory fades with age. In fact, the opposite is closer to the truth. Memories do not replay events as they happened. They rebuild and reshape our experiences each time we pull them up. It is easy to test this on our own. Looking back at old notes, we may wonder if we wrote them. It happens for a few reasons. First, when we remember events, the emotional charge matters more than the weight of the event. As a result, the memories that stick in our minds are odd, scary, or funny. Second, we often zero in on the past details that matter to us now, reshaping how we read them to fit our current needs. Build a nighttime routine that signals your brain to wind down, which lifts sleep and mental recovery. To fix these thinking mistakes, we should first spot them and write down the typical situations where they show up. The next step is to build fresh thinking patterns. For example, under the planning fallacy, we tend to plan less time for tasks than they take. So when we set a deadline, we should not guess. We should look back at how long the task took last time. This is called cognitive revision, and it is a strong tool for the planning fallacy. Another well known tool for stopping faulty thinking is the consider the opposite method. By arguing against our own view, we can spot the holes and weak spots. Since situations and biases differ, we should be creative in replacing shortcuts with reliable patterns. Neurologists believe some memory and thinking skills start to slip by the late twenties.'
      },
      {
        title: 'What the inner voice tells us',
        text: 'After seeing how bent our view of reality can be, we may comfort ourselves by thinking we at least know what we want. Sadly, this is a kind of self trick. We like to think we run our own lives, but the numbers show that mistakes in self reflection are surprisingly common. Why. Old and new thinkers have pointed to a few common reasons. Picking up ready made ideas and giving in to bias are among the biggest. Holding on to the illusion of control, we tend to overstate our grip on events, tying random outcomes to our actions. This bias also makes us jump to fast calls about whether events are lucky or unlucky. We never really know. Some bad luck may turn into a win in a few years. So what we really face are oversimplifications. Spending time alone is not just for introverts. It is one of the least talked about and most needed parts of a healthy life, as Ryan A. Bush has noted. So how can we shape our inner voice in a useful way. First, step away from distractions like phones and laptops with a slow walk. Second, reframe self questions with what instead of why. For example, instead of why do I feel unhappy, try what makes me think I am unhappy. Using what is more specific and opens the door to a more honest inner talk. Asking yourself personal questions is a strong way to build a calm relationship with yourself. We can reflect on our best traits, our lifestyle, or our future goals by asking questions that define who we are. For example, we can ask what makes us happy or what we want to reach. The inner sense will answer, and we should write down the small aha moments. They will help us see our feelings and dreams more clearly. Anything that helps us break out of old thinking can lead to fresh insight. Mindfulness practice or even a change of scene, like a trip, can lift our thinking power. Another way to know ourselves better is to map our values. A simple method can help. After brainstorming and listing the people we admire, we should write down the traits that draw us to them. Those traits are likely to be our own values.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Ways to work with our feelings',
        text: 'Once we have pushed back on biases, we can turn to another pillar of the psyche, which is emotion. Emotions have helped us survive as a species, so we need all of them. Still, we should not let them wreck our choices. Aristotle believed that happiness is not calm or the absence of bad feelings. It is the right feelings in the right amounts. So the trick is not to wipe out anger or fear, but to use them well. Resentment, for example, can drive us forward or pull us down, depending on the rules we run. How do we grow responses that put our goals first, not our gut. Here are some ways to reprogram our reactions to feelings. Anger is our alarm system, and it signals when others cross our lines. It also shows up when we are stressed, tired, or turned down, making us irritated at the world. It is not the best mood for hitting our goals. So when our heart races and our muscles tense, we should remember that we are the biggest victim of our own anger. As Stoic thinker Seneca once said, simply pausing our reaction to anger can save our mental and emotional energy. Shame is tied to missing social expectations. So if we want to reprogram this feeling, we should depend less on social status and on the approval of others. We also need to be careful about taking on accusations. Some people may try to pin their own feelings or traits on us in unfair ways. Envy can lock us in a loop of constant disappointment with what we have. To break the loop, we should cut the roots, which is the habit of comparing with others. When we look at someone post and think I do not have it, let us recall where we were five years ago. Anxiety is the next feeling. A well known saying tells us not to worry about things we cannot change, since a nervous breakdown helps no one. Another way to handle it is to stay in the present. Anxiety points our mind to future events, so coming back to the here and now is a strong way to ease the worry. How others treat you shows more about them than about your worth.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Tips to make actions match our goals',
        text: 'Habits are our thoughts and feelings in action. So mastering them is a must if we want to reach our goals in real life, not only in our heads. Many people think self control is the only answer to staying on track. Willpower is strong, but it is a finite resource. So it pays to have a plan B that helps us reach our goals. The first way to strengthen good habits is intentional environment design. This method means avoiding triggers of bad habits and adding chances to practice good ones. For example, if we want to lose weight, we can plan our routes to skip our favorite bakeries. We can also join classes on healthy cooking. Often, even plain foods come alive with the right prep. If we want to learn meditation, we can sign up for a retreat. That way, we have no choice but to practice. Our surroundings shape us a lot, so we should pick them with care. This rule applies to both the physical and the digital space. If we want to run a business, we should listen to podcasts and visit sites recommended by people who have already done it. Rewards push you more than punishments do. Another way to spread good habits is cognitive reappraisal. It is when we use our mind to make a hard but healthy option feel more attractive. Often, the task is what we make of it. Say we need to write a tough report. Let us make the work look like a game, with levels, tokens, and small rewards. Rewards are useful, but only for tasks with no room for creativity. For creative work, the carrot and stick approach can backfire. That is because it crushes our internal drive, which is far more powerful than any outside push. Studies show that students driven by an inner wish to learn win more recognition. So how do we tap into that. Three parts lift our internal drive. First, autonomy. Inventing our own way to handle a task gives us energy. Second, mastery. Doing an activity that sharpens our skills pushes us to work harder. Third, purpose. When we link the task to a bigger goal, the boost in drive is sure. Do not try to be the best. Be the only one, as Kevin Kelly has said.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Many people think it is impossible to change by working on the mind. But handling our biases, stereotypes, bad habits, and fears is a proven way to reach more of our potential. The trick is to find the techniques that work for us. For example, if we do not like running but want to stay healthy, we can play tennis. It is just as hard on the body and gives us fun challenges. If our goal is to drop bad habits, we can start by spotting the triggers of our bad patterns. Once we know where the bad feelings come from, we can cut the link. Next, we should try different rewards, pushing ourselves to take on good habits. Once we find the approach that fires us up the most, we can use it for tough challenges. The bottom line is that if we want methods that suit us better, we should try things out. If we want to dig into our inner world, we can turn to cognitive therapy, which gives the basic skills. Great thinkers believe that the best way to live a good life is to use our own mind, not the standards others set. Our thoughts shape what we do, which shapes our character and so our fate. So managing our beliefs and feelings is the key to taking charge of our lives and lifting how we perform. Try this. Make a list of the habits you want to drop. In front of each one, write down your reactions in every situation. This will help you see what to avoid and what to welcome. Celebrate your wins, no matter how small. That will support you in building a better version of yourself. Build a motivational playlist with inspiring songs, videos, or series to push through low energy days. If you have read to the end, well done.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'designing-your-work-life.json': {
    base: { id: 'designing-your-work-life', title: 'Designing Your Work Life', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781615372659 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Design thinking is a way to bring meaning into your work',
        text: 'The modern workplace is in a state of constant change. Companies keep shifting, getting more agile, and moving faster to meet new demands. In this shifting world, it is up to workers to define their own success and joy. With that, you can avoid staying in a job that does not bring you happiness. Management teams should work with their staff to find a fair middle ground, and they should offer resources to build the right culture at work. The culture should help workers feel at ease with the fast changes around them as the business adapts to new market needs. Since we spend most of our time at work, we look to our jobs to give us meaning and impact. A dream work life is the shared job of the company and each worker. As a worker, you can build a plan that highlights the meaning and impact of what you do. There is no point in waiting for change to show up on its own. You have to act to make it happen. In this summary, you will learn more about designing your life in a way that brings you joy. How can you turn work into a place of strength and joy. Why is it sometimes smart to set the bar low for your role and the people around you. You will find the answers here. You will also learn that quitting is not always a bad move, and not something to avoid by default. Following this advice, you will become happier, healthier, and more productive. Turn the page to learn more.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Do not wait for happiness, work toward what you want',
        text: 'Waiting for a happy place to show up on its own is a waste of energy. A better paying job does not always lift our lives. The point is whether we know how to value what we have now and where we are headed. If the work matches our values and fits a stage of our growth, it will bring satisfaction. But how can we know if a given activity is right for us. We should pay attention to our feelings. When we feel anger, irritation, and despair, that is a signal that we are not meeting our needs. To change it, we have to act. Do not worry if you are not where you want to be. The job you have now is a stepping stone. That does not mean you should settle for a job that does not fulfill you, but the grass is not always greener. Of course, this way of thinking does not apply when work leaves you drained and is the cause of depression. But knowing that what you do is okay for now is a useful way to reframe the situation. You take the first step toward change by letting go of useless complaints and accepting the facts. Yes, you may not have your dream job yet, but if you can work and earn, that is good. Now you can think about how to make things better. What does it mean to reframe. It means labeling something in a new way. We should know the gap between a healthy reframe and a harmful one. Simply saying that your job is great, engaging, and well paid is not enough. Real change is needed to improve the situation. It may sound like a huge task, but the effort can be small. Small steps matter a lot. When we look for ways to make work more enjoyable, we are redesigning. To see this better, imagine you are fixing up your home. First, you walk around and check the state. Next, you picture what you want. Repaint the walls, swap the furniture, or even change the layout. Then you bring the plan to life. The same applies to redesigning life situations. Before you chase new ones, see if you can lift the ones you have.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Make the most of a bad spot by trying to change it',
        text: 'You probably know the saying, when life gives you lemons, make lemonade. Sometimes turning a bad spot into a good one works. For example, a vacation can ease the problem for a while if you feel worn out at work. But if all you do is make the best of a bad spot, it is still bad. The deep problem has not moved. You will feel better for a bit, but it is like patching a leaky pipe that will burst again later. Reframing means looking at the situation with care and setting aside strong feelings and exaggerations. Let us say you are thinking of leaving your job because you do not feel valued. You are flooded with feelings, and your first urge is to quit. Give yourself time for the feelings to settle. Then ask, what is happening with me right now, and what do I need. These questions help you see the situation from another side and find a fix. Do not wait. Ask your boss for feedback on your work. You can even ask for that feedback on a regular basis. You will reshape your work life by using a new way of thinking. It may not be fast or simple, but it will pay off and you can do it. Another method is the Set the Bar Low method, which says we need to start with small steps to reach bigger goals. You cannot write a book in one night. Writing 200 to 400 words a day is doable. To find joy in what you do, set goals you can hit, do them, and repeat. The mindset of always chasing more often leaves us feeling unfulfilled and down. When we chase the perfect job, car, house, or city, we never stop. Sometimes it helps to see the value in what you already have. Long term memory works best between 6 and 7 in the morning, and the brain soaks up information from that time with little effort.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Do not use the wrong compass for work and life',
        text: 'Do you put money over meaning in life. Many people wrestle with that question. So what do you pick. There is no single right answer, since it is a false split. Money and meaning are not enemies. They are different ways of measuring what you value. Many people have fancy jobs and still feel empty. A prestigious title does not guarantee meaning. At the same time, you can find a lot of meaning in work that pays very little. You can also have both money and meaning in the same work. Whichever you lean toward between money and meaning is not the point. What matters is a coherent life, where your values and your actions line up to make you happy. We often live someone else life without seeing it. We work around the clock because our parents told us that only people with a successful career win respect. Ask yourself if you agree with that view. If not, you are unlikely to feel at peace. Start small, set the bar low, and try something, as Bill Burnett has said. Your life is coherent when your identity, beliefs, and actions agree. To build a coherent life, you need to form clear views of work and life. The work view is your idea of what makes a job worth doing or not. When you build a work view, it is key to know why you work, what your work means, and how you affect others. A life view is your own take on what gives life purpose and value. A life view is what helps us see what matters most. It answers the big questions. We want to know the purpose of our lives. To find our life compass, we need to look at where we are and name the point we want to reach. A 2015 Lancet study found that people who work more than 55 hours a week face a higher risk of stroke, about 1.3 times the risk of those who stick to a standard week.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Build a healthy mindset to feel engaged and whole',
        text: 'When we feel stuck in a rut, we often look to blame other things or people around us. We do not need to point fingers to move forward. Let us face the truth. The people around us do not decide our happiness. We are not hostages to the situation. It is our choice to be where we are. If we do not like the company we work for or our boss, we are the only ones who can do something about it. Life design means taking ownership of your choices. You are the one who can start making positive changes to move toward joy on every level. There are two types of mindset, based on research by Stanford professor Carol Dweck. They are the fixed mind and the growth mind. People with a fixed mind believe that each of us has a fixed set of natural talents that we cannot change. They think they can only become an artist if they were born with that gift. When they are good at something, they chalk it up to natural talent, not to practice and growth. People with a growth mind believe that natural talent is not the only thing that decides success. Everyone has a starting point, but we can all grow and reach new heights. We only need to work on our skills in a steady way. They credit success to hard work and discipline, not to natural gifts. People with a fixed mind often have a harder time with failure and do not try to change the situation. They push the cause of the loss onto outside factors. The good news is that no matter where you start, you can shift. If you have a fixed mind now, you can retune it to a growth mind with practice and training. Whenever you catch yourself thinking in a fixed way, look at the situation from another angle and suggest what you can do to lift it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Do not quit your job, redesign it',
        text: 'Sometimes you are bored with your job and fed up. Maybe you started a career and never planned to stay, but many years have passed and you are still there. Do not quit. Not yet. You do not have to stay in this job forever. Nor should you hold on at all costs. But people often act on impulse and make fast calls, missing the chance to make things better in the same spot. Sometimes staying is more effective than starting from scratch. Redesigning our lives can be hard, and starting over from zero can be even harder. It is better to try all your redesign moves before you opt for a full reset. Life design is about building many options and prototypes for the life you want. There are several ways to change a situation that does not fit you. Depending on the setting, one of these will work. The first path is relabel and re enlist. Try to find a fresh spark in your work. Recall what drew you to it in the first place. Feel free to share new ideas and solutions. Figure out what you need to feel valued and give it to yourself. Sometimes small things, like a more comfortable desk or steady feedback from your boss, can lift the situation. Reframing and re enlisting are good ways to make things good enough for now. It is pretty simple. Take things as they are. Find new reasons for what you do. Redefine your bond with work. Refresh your interest in the role. Find reasons to stay motivated on the job. The second path is redesign. Why not make a structural or even a cosmetic change to the job you already have. That way you are rebuilding and refreshing it. For example, moving to another department or trying a new direction in the same company is a structural change. It takes extra effort, but it can be the fastest way out of a tough spot. Life design is a journey, so let go of the end goal and focus on the process and see what comes next, as Bill Burnett has said.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Reframe quitting as a choice and leave with purpose',
        text: 'Nothing in life stays the same forever, and everything has to change at some point. You are unlikely to work for the same company your whole life. Change and newness are needed for growth, so learning to quit the right way is key. Quitting can happen in many ways, but they all fall into two camps. The first type burns bridges. It usually shows someone storming out in a flash, without a care. No matter how bad things get, you should not give in to your base instincts. Walk out the door with your dignity and the relationship intact. Anger and irritation have no place when you tell a company you are leaving. The second type gives two weeks notice. It is used thousands of times a day and often looks like this. The person decides they want to quit. They pick the date they will leave. They tell the company in a respectful way, two weeks before the date. This way of leaving is correct, but it can still be better. If you are in a setting you cannot control, this is fine. It is not as harmful as the first way, but it is not helpful either. Then there is generative quitting. Reframing is useful not only in work changes but also in the process of changing jobs. It all depends on how you read the situation. You can see the need to leave as a bad thing or as an open door for new chances. The end of the old always means the start of the new. You have gained experience you can now use elsewhere. See a layoff as a chance to grow. To step into the next stage with joy, we need to close the previous one with thanks. You surely have reasons to be grateful for the time you spent. You just need to notice them. People who quit in a generative way know how important it is to leave the employer on good terms. As a result, they limit the damage and end up with a far better outcome.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Designing a life is always a journey with no finish line. The unknown of what comes next can be unsettling, yet it is also what makes life feel alive. Of course, sometimes our plans fall apart, and we need to pause, take a breath, and take stock. That often means starting again, and that is fine. Once you adopt design thinking, you will keep moving forward, because you will always have at least a rough sense of what is next. Your wins may even top your hopes. Building a life is a process that never ends, and it is never polished, but it can be good enough. We know that life is short and far too short to be spent dreading the workday. Each of us deserves to feel at peace with the hours we give to our work. Take a moment to ask the following. Do you have to drag yourself to the office. Do you feel a sting of irritation when you deal with coworkers and managers. Are you content with the output you produce. Do you feel tense and worn out once a workday ends. If most of your answers lean yes, burnout may be near. Now is the time to look after yourself. Try this. Write out your work view and your life view. What shifts do you need to make in your days and your job so what you do lines up with the values you hold. Keep a journal and scan for patterns in any body signs you notice, like a sore back or pounding head. It may be a quiet signal of burnout. Try to keep a positive mindset. Reframe any dark thought that pops up. If you have read to the end, well done.'
      }
    ]
  }
};
